The <b>Plain Wren</b> (<i><b>Cantorchilus modestus</b></i>) is a species of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird" title="Bird">bird</a> in the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troglodytidae" title="Troglodytidae" class="mw-redirect">Troglodytidae</a> family. It is found in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belize" title="Belize">Belize</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Costa_Rica" title="Costa Rica">Costa Rica</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/El_Salvador" title="El Salvador">El Salvador</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guatemala" title="Guatemala">Guatemala</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Honduras" title="Honduras">Honduras</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mexico" title="Mexico">Mexico</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicaragua" title="Nicaragua">Nicaragua</a>, and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Panama" title="Panama">Panama</a>. Its natural <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitat" title="Habitat">habitats</a> are subtropical or tropical dry <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forest" title="Forest">forests</a>, subtropical or tropical moist lowland forests, and heavily degraded former forest.
The <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subspecies" title="Subspecies">subspecies</a> <i>zeledoni</i> of eastern Nicaragua, eastern Costa Rica and north-west Panama is sometimes considered to be a separate species, <b>Canebrake Wren</b>.
